free_txt: Two C6D6 liquid scintillators placed at 125 deg
with respect to sample
Silicon detectors for 6Li(n,t)4He detection for
flux shape measurement
235U and 238U fission detection for flux
shape measurement
CERN nTOF facility.
Protons (3 to 7E+12 protons/pulse, pulse width of
6 nsec) were accelerated to 20 GeV with typical
repetition rate of 0.4 Hz.
Neutrons were produced in a Pb spallation
target.
The neutron flux shape was determined by detection of
6Li(n,t) reaction products by four Si detectors, and
also detection of 235U and 238U fission by a fission
chamber.
Low efficiency detectors to which the
Pulse-Height Weighting Technique is applied in order
to make the detection efficiency proportional to the
gamma-ray energy.
Flight path length (moderator-detector)=185.20 m.
Si detector
C6D6 detectors
Yield correction, weighting function
Bi sample (20 mm in diam., 6.1 mm in thickness),
Au monitor foil (20 mm in diam., 1 mm in thickness).
Approved by Cesar Domingo-Pardo (2016-02-17)
No information on source of uncertainty
The partial uncertainties in the capture yield due the
following three correction factors are treated as
fully correlated uncertainties in the R-matrix
analysis:
- Yield correction factor
(which uncertainty is 1% and energy independent)
- Neutron sensitivity correction
(which uncertainty is 20%, only for the 12.1 keV
s-wave resonance)
- Normalization via the 4.9 eV Au resonance
(which uncertainty is energy independent)
Area of the broad s-wave resonance at 12.098 keV
plus two p-wave resonances at 12.092 and 12.285 keV
Main source of L, J and Gamma(n)
Table II of Phys.Rev.C74(2006)025807
Calculated based on the new resonance parameters
complemented by resonances at 25 to 31 keV by
P.Mutti et al., and 31 to 60 keV by S.F.Mughabghab
Propagated from the uncertainties in the
resonance parameters determined in this work as well
as those in the resonance parameters from Mutti and
in the capture areas from Mughabghab.
